T*
(## 1.1 Definitions and the Reality?Virtuality Continuum) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Virtual Reality \(VR\)** is a fully simulated, computer-generated environment that replaces the) Tj
T*
(user's real-world perception. The user is immersed in a 3D digital world through a head-mounted) Tj
T*
(display \(HMD\) with tracking sensors, auditory feedback, and sometimes haptic feedback.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Augmented Reality \(AR\)** overlays computer-generated content \(images, 3D objects,) Tj
T*
(annotations\) onto the real world in real time. The user continues to see the real world, but) Tj
T*
(with digital enhancements layered on top.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Mixed Reality \(MR\)** is sometimes used as a synonym for AR or as a distinct category where) Tj
T*
(virtual and real objects coexist and interact.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Paul Milgram's **Reality?Virtuality Continuum \(1994\)** arranges these on a spectrum:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(```) Tj
T*
(Real Environment ???????????????????? Virtual Environment) Tj
T*
(                  AR     MR     AV) Tj
T*
(```) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- **AR \(Augmented Reality\):** Mostly real, supplemented by virtual) Tj
T*
(- **AV \(Augmented Virtuality\):** Mostly virtual, supplemented by real elements) Tj
T*
(- **VR:** Completely virtual) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(## 1.2 How VR Systems Work) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(A VR system has four critical subsystems:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 1.2.1 Tracking and Pose Estimation) Tj
T*
(The system must know exactly where the user's head \(and hands\) are at all times.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- **6 Degrees of Freedom \(6-DoF\):** Three translational \(x, y, z\) + three rotational \(pitch,) Tj
T*
(yaw, roll\)) Tj
T*
(- **Inside-out tracking:** Cameras on the headset observe the environment \(Meta Quest,) Tj
T*
(HoloLens\)) Tj
T*
(- **Outside-in tracking:** External base stations emit infrared light or radio signals that the) Tj
T*
(headset detects \(Valve Index, original HTC Vive\)) Tj
T*
(- **IMU \(Inertial Measurement Unit\):** Accelerometer + gyroscope for fast rotational tracking;) Tj
T*
(fused with visual tracking via a Kalman filter) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 1.2.2 Rendering Pipeline) Tj
T*
(VR requires **two images** \(one per eye\) rendered at very high frame rates:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(| Requirement | Typical Specification |) Tj
T*
(|---|---|) Tj
T*
(| Minimum frame rate | 72 fps \(discomfort below this\) |) Tj
T*
(| Ideal frame rate | 90?120 fps |) Tj
T*
(| Resolution per eye | 20002000 pixels \(modern headsets\) |) Tj
T*
(| Latency \(motion-to-photon\) | <20 ms \(to prevent nausea\) |) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Foveated rendering:** Because the eye's fovea \(high-acuity region\) covers only ~2 of visual) Tj
T*
(field, eye-tracking allows the GPU to render only the gaze point in full resolution, reducing) Tj
T*
(GPU load by 30?70%.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Reprojection / Asynchronous Timewarp \(ATW\):** If a frame is late, the GPU extrapolates the) Tj
T*
(new head orientation from the pose data and warps the previous frame rather than displaying a) Tj
T*
(stale or missing image. This prevents judder.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 1.2.3 Display Technologies) Tj
T*
(- **LCD:** Fast-switching IPS panels used in many consumer headsets) Tj
T*
(- **OLED:** Higher contrast, true blacks, but risk of persistence/ghosting; used in PlayStation) Tj
T*
(VR) Tj
T*
(- **Pancake Optics:** Fold light back and forth to create thin lenses \(Meta Quest 3, Apple) Tj
T*
