BT
/F1 9 Tf
11 TL
54 738 Td
(- Dual graph of the Voronoi diagram: connect circumcenters of adjacent triangles) Tj
T*
(- Unique in general position \(no 4 co-circular points\)) Tj
T*
(- For n points: O\(n log n\) time to compute; produces at most 2n ? h ? 2 triangles \(h = convex) Tj
T*
(hull points\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Circumcircle condition \(Delaunay condition\):**  ) Tj
T*
(For each edge shared by triangles T1 and T2: the fourth point of T2 must NOT lie inside the) Tj
T*
(circumcircle of T1 \(and vice versa\). If it does, the shared edge is "flipped.") Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Bowyer?Watson Algorithm:**) Tj
T*
(```) Tj
T*
(1. Start with a super-triangle containing all points) Tj
T*
(2. For each point p:) Tj
T*
(   a. Find all triangles whose circumcircle contains p  \(bad triangles\)) Tj
T*
(   b. Find the boundary polygon of the bad triangles \(the "hole"\)) Tj
T*
(   c. Delete bad triangles; re-triangulate the hole with p as new vertex) Tj
T*
(3. Remove triangles sharing vertices with the super-triangle) Tj
T*
(```) Tj
T*
(Time complexity: O\(n log n\) average, O\(n\) worst case.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Lawson Flipping Algorithm:**  ) Tj
T*
(Start with any valid triangulation; iteratively flip non-Delaunay edges until all edges satisfy) Tj
T*
(the Delaunay condition. O\(n\) in worst case but fast in practice.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 2.2.3 3D Triangulation from Point Clouds) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Ball Pivoting Algorithm \(BPA\):**  ) Tj
T*
(Imagine a ball of radius ? rolling over the point cloud:) Tj
T*
(1. Seed: find three points that form a triangle and have the ball resting on them with no other) Tj
T*
(point inside) Tj
T*
(2. Pivot: roll the ball around each edge; the next triangle vertex is the first point the ball) Tj
T*
(touches) Tj
T*
(3. Continue until all points are reached or the ball gets stuck in a hole) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The radius ? determines the mesh resolution. Multiple passes with different ? can recover fine) Tj
T*
(and coarse features.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Poisson Surface Reconstruction \(Kazhdan et al., 2006\):**  ) Tj
T*
(One of the most widely used methods:) Tj
T*
(1. Estimate oriented point normals) Tj
T*
(2. Formulate surface reconstruction as solving a Poisson equation: ?? = ?**V**, where **V**) Tj
T*
(is the vector field of normals and ? is an indicator function \(1 inside, 0 outside\)) Tj
T*
(3. Extract the isosurface ? = 0.5 using Marching Cubes) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Advantages: robust to noise, produces watertight closed meshes. Used in MeshLab, Open3D, PCL.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Alpha Shapes:**  ) Tj
T*
(A generalization of Delaunay triangulation. For a parameter ?, delete all simplices \(triangles,) Tj
T*
(edges, vertices\) whose circumradius exceeds 1/?. The result is a subset of the Delaunay) Tj
T*
(triangulation that follows the shape of the point cloud.) Tj
T*
(- Large ? ? convex hull) Tj
T*
(- Small ? ? detailed concave shape, or potentially disconnected) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Marching Cubes Algorithm \(Lorensen & Cline, 1987\):**  ) Tj
T*
(Used to extract an isosurface from a volumetric scalar field \(e.g., CT voxels\):) Tj
T*
(1. Divide space into small cubes) Tj
T*
(2. At each cube corner, evaluate whether the scalar value is above or below the iso-threshold) Tj
T*
(3. There are 2? = 256 possible configurations \(reduced to 15 by symmetry\); each corresponds to) Tj
T*
(a set of triangles within the cube) Tj
T*
(4. Interpolate edge intersection points; output triangles) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This is the standard algorithm for medical image segmentation and volume rendering.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 2.2.4 Summary Table: Triangulation Methods) Tj
T*
