T*
(## 2.4 Hole Filling and Surface Reconstruction) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 2.4.1 What are Holes?) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Holes in a mesh arise from:) Tj
T*
(- Missing data during scanning \(occluded regions, reflective surfaces, scanner limitations\)) Tj
T*
(- Deliberate removal of corrupted regions) Tj
T*
(- Errors in reconstruction algorithms) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(A hole is a **boundary loop** in the mesh ? a chain of boundary edges forming a closed polygon.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 2.4.2 Simple Hole Filling Methods) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Ear Clipping / Triangulation of the Boundary Polygon:**  ) Tj
T*
(1. Identify the boundary loop \(ordered sequence of boundary vertices v?, v?, ..., v?\)) Tj
T*
(2. Triangulate the polygon formed by these vertices) Tj
T*
(3. The simplest approach: connect each adjacent triple \(v???, v?, v???\) creating "ears") Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This produces a flat patch. For small holes, it is adequate.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Minimum-Area Triangulation:**  ) Tj
T*
(Among all possible triangulations of the boundary polygon, choose the one minimizing total) Tj
T*
(triangle area. Can be computed in O\(n\) using dynamic programming.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 2.4.3 Feature-Preserving Hole Filling \(Zhao et al., 2007\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(For larger or more complex holes, the fill must match the surrounding surface curvature:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(1. **Boundary analysis:** Detect curvature and normals along the hole boundary) Tj
T*
(2. **Initial fill:** Apply a rough triangulation to the hole) Tj
T*
(3. **Refinement:** Iteratively move interior vertices to minimize a fairness energy functional:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(```) Tj
T*
(E = ?_fair  E_fairness + ?_fit  E_fit) Tj
T*
(```) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(where E_fairness penalizes high curvature \(Laplacian smoothing\) and E_fit attracts the patch) Tj
T*
(toward known data.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Laplacian smoothing step:**  ) Tj
T*
(For each interior vertex v: v ? \(1/|N|\) ? v? over all neighbors N\(v\)  ) Tj
T*
(Repeated application smooths the patch to match neighbors.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 2.4.4 Poisson-Based Reconstruction for Holes) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The same Poisson surface reconstruction \(Section 2.2.3\) can be applied to a partial mesh with) Tj
T*
(holes:) Tj
T*
(1. Sample additional points around the hole boundary) Tj
T*
(2. Estimate their normals by interpolation from surrounding normals) Tj
T*
(3. Run full Poisson reconstruction on the combined point set) Tj
T*
(4. The algorithm naturally fills holes because it solves a global equation) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 2.4.5 Deep Learning Approaches) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Recent methods use neural networks for hole filling:) Tj
T*
(- **PCN \(Point Completion Network\):** Takes incomplete point cloud; encoder-decoder outputs) Tj
T*
(completed point cloud) Tj
T*
(- **FoldingNet, TopNet, PoinTr:** Various architectures for point cloud completion) Tj
T*
(- Used when the missing part can be inferred from context \(e.g., the other half of a symmetric) Tj
T*
(object\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(## 2.5 Noise Removal and Point Set Regularization) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
