BT
/F1 9 Tf
11 TL
54 738 Td
(**Disadvantages:**) Tj
T*
(- Ionizing radiation \(cumulative dose risk\)) Tj
T*
(- Poor soft-tissue contrast \(compared to MRI\)) Tj
T*
(- Artifacts: beam hardening, metal artifacts, partial volume effect) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(## 3.2 MRI Scanning \(Magnetic Resonance Imaging\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 3.2.1 Physical Principle) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(MRI exploits the **nuclear magnetic resonance \(NMR\)** of hydrogen nuclei \(protons\).) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(1. **Alignment:** A strong static magnetic field B? \(1.5T, 3T, or 7T\) aligns proton spins) Tj
T*
(parallel or anti-parallel to the field) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(2. **Excitation:** A radiofrequency \(RF\) pulse at the Larmor frequency  ) Tj
T*
(   `f_L = ? B? / \(2?\)`  ) Tj
T*
(   \(? = 42.577 MHz/T for hydrogen\) tips the net magnetization into the transverse plane) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(3. **Relaxation:** After the RF pulse, two relaxation processes occur:) Tj
T*
(   - **T1 \(longitudinal relaxation\):** Magnetization recovers along B?; different tissues have) Tj
T*
(different T1 times) Tj
T*
(   - **T2 \(transverse relaxation\):** Transverse magnetization decays due to spin-spin) Tj
T*
(interactions; also tissue-specific) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(4. **Signal detection:** The relaxing magnetization induces a voltage in receiver coils ? the) Tj
T*
(**FID \(Free Induction Decay\)** signal) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(5. **Spatial encoding:** Gradient coils create spatially varying magnetic fields. The frequency) Tj
T*
(and phase of the signal encode position. **2D Fourier transform** of the collected k-space data) Tj
T*
(produces the image.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 3.2.2 MRI Sequences and Weighting) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(By choosing the **Repetition Time \(TR\)** and **Echo Time \(TE\)**, different tissue contrasts are) Tj
T*
(achieved:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(| Sequence | TR | TE | Bright | Uses |) Tj
T*
(|---|---|---|---|---|) Tj
T*
(| T1-weighted | Short | Short | Fat, contrast-enhancing lesions | Anatomy, post-contrast brain) Tj
T*
(|) Tj
T*
(| T2-weighted | Long | Long | Fluid, edema, CSF | Pathology detection, brain |) Tj
T*
(| PD-weighted | Long | Short | Proton density | Cartilage, joint imaging |) Tj
T*
(| FLAIR | Long | Long \(fluid suppressed\) | White matter lesions | MS, encephalitis |) Tj
T*
(| DWI \(diffusion\) | ? | ? | Restricted diffusion \(ischemia\) | Stroke, tumor cellularity |) Tj
T*
(| fMRI \(BOLD\) | ? | ? | Blood oxygenation | Brain activity mapping |) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### 3.2.3 MRI Advantages and Disadvantages) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Advantages:**) Tj
T*
(- No ionizing radiation) Tj
T*
(- Excellent soft-tissue contrast \(brain, spinal cord, joint cartilage, liver\)) Tj
T*
(- Multi-parametric: T1, T2, DWI, perfusion, spectroscopy in one session) Tj
T*
(- Functional imaging possible \(fMRI, DTI\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(**Disadvantages:**) Tj
T*
(- Long acquisition time \(minutes vs. seconds for CT\)) Tj
T*
(- Loud noise \(gradient switching\)) Tj
T*
(- Contraindicated in patients with certain metal implants \(pacemakers, some stents\)) Tj
T*
(- Expensive, less widely available) Tj
T*
(- Susceptibility to motion artifacts) Tj
T*
(- Limited spatial resolution for some applications) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(## 3.3 3D Reconstruction from Medical Scans) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
