(# Bzier Curves ? Complete Reference) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(> *Wikipedia says:* "A Bzier curve is a parametric curve used in computer graphics and related) Tj
T*
(fields. A set of discrete 'control points' defines a smooth, continuous curve by means of a) Tj
T*
(formula. The Bzier curve is named after French engineer Pierre Bzier \(1910?1999\), who used it) Tj
T*
(in the 1960s for designing curves for the bodywork of Renault cars.") Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(---) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(## 1. History) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(| Person | Company | Year | Contribution |) Tj
T*
(|---|---|---|---|) Tj
T*
(| Paul de Casteljau | Citron | 1959 | Recursive algorithm \(unpublished until 1980s\) |) Tj
T*
(| Pierre Bzier | Renault | 1960s | Publicly described polynomial-based curves \(UNISURF\) |) Tj
T*
(| Sergei Bernstein | ? | 1912 | Bernstein basis polynomials \(mathematical foundation\) |) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Both de Casteljau and Bzier independently discovered the same mathematical curves built on) Tj
T*
(Bernstein polynomials. The algorithm is named after de Casteljau; the curves after Bzier.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(---) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
