(To compute a point on a Bzier surface, we apply De Casteljau's algorithm in two dimensions.) Tj
T*
(You can think of a Bzier surface as a grid of control points. First, we use the parameter u to) Tj
T*
(evaluate a point along each row of the grid. This yields a new, single "column" of intermediate) Tj
T*
(points. Then, we use the parameter v to evaluate that new column, which gives us our final 3D) Tj
T*
(point on the surface.) Tj
T*
(Here is the complete, self-contained TypeScript code to evaluate a Bzier surface, including a) Tj
T*
(function to generate a full mesh of points so you can render it.) Tj
T*
(### 1. The Bzier Surface Implementation) Tj
T*
(```typescript) Tj
T*
(export interface Point3D {) Tj
T*
(    x: number;) Tj
T*
(    y: number;) Tj
T*
(    z: number;) Tj
T*
(}) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(/**) Tj
T*
( * Helper function: De Casteljau's algorithm for a 1D curve in 3D space.) Tj
T*
( */) Tj
T*
(function deCasteljau3D\(points: Point3D[], t: number\): Point3D {) Tj
T*
(    if \(points.length === 0\) {) Tj
T*
(        throw new Error\("At least one control point is required."\);) Tj
T*
(    }) Tj
T*
(    ) Tj
T*
(    const workingPoints: Point3D[] = points.map\(p => \({ x: p.x, y: p.y, z: p.z }\)\);) Tj
T*
(    const n = workingPoints.length - 1;) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(    for \(let j = 1; j <= n; j++\) {) Tj
T*
(        for \(let i = 0; i <= n - j; i++\) {) Tj
T*
(            workingPoints[i] = {) Tj
T*
(                x: \(1 - t\) * workingPoints[i].x + t * workingPoints[i + 1].x,) Tj
T*
(                y: \(1 - t\) * workingPoints[i].y + t * workingPoints[i + 1].y,) Tj
T*
(                z: \(1 - t\) * workingPoints[i].z + t * workingPoints[i + 1].z) Tj
T*
(            };) Tj
T*
(        }) Tj
T*
(    }) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(    return workingPoints[0];) Tj
T*
(}) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(/**) Tj
T*
( * Evaluates a specific \(u, v\) point on a Bezier surface.) Tj
T*
( * @param controlGrid - A 2D array [row][col] of 3D control points.) Tj
T*
( * @param u - The parameter u, typically between 0.0 and 1.0.) Tj
T*
( * @param v - The parameter v, typically between 0.0 and 1.0.) Tj
T*
( * @returns The evaluated 3D point on the surface.) Tj
T*
( */) Tj
T*
(export function evaluateBezierSurface\(controlGrid: Point3D[][], u: number, v: number\): Point3D) Tj
T*
({) Tj
T*
(    if \(controlGrid.length === 0 || controlGrid[0].length === 0\) {) Tj
T*
(        throw new Error\("Control grid cannot be empty."\);) Tj
T*
(    }) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(    const uCurvePoints: Point3D[] = [];) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
