T*
(### 2. Usage Example) Tj
T*
(To test this, we can define a biquadratic surface \(a 3 \\times 3 grid of control points\). This) Tj
T*
(creates a simple curved "sheet" in 3D space.) Tj
T*
(```typescript) Tj
T*
(// Define a 3x3 grid of control points \(Biquadratic Bezier Surface\)) Tj
T*
(const surfaceControlGrid: Point3D[][] = [) Tj
T*
(    // Row 0) Tj
T*
(    [ {x: -10, y: -10, z: 0}, {x: 0, y: -10, z: 5}, {x: 10, y: -10, z: 0} ],) Tj
T*
(    // Row 1) Tj
T*
(    [ {x: -10, y: 0, z: 5},   {x: 0, y: 0, z: 10},  {x: 10, y: 0, z: 5}   ],) Tj
T*
(    // Row 2) Tj
T*
(    [ {x: -10, y: 10, z: 0},  {x: 0, y: 10, z: 5},  {x: 10, y: 10, z: 0}  ]) Tj
T*
(];) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(// 1. Evaluate a single point in the dead center of the surface) Tj
T*
(const centerPoint = evaluateBezierSurface\(surfaceControlGrid, 0.5, 0.5\);) Tj
T*
(console.log\(`Center point \(u=0.5, v=0.5\): x=${centerPoint.x}, y=${centerPoint.y},) Tj
T*
(z=${centerPoint.z}`\);) Tj
T*
(// Output: Center point \(u=0.5, v=0.5\): x=0, y=0, z=6.25) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(// 2. Generate a coarse mesh \(4x4 points\) for rendering) Tj
T*
(const resolution = 3; // 3 segments means 4 points along each axis) Tj
T*
(const mesh = generateSurfaceMesh\(surfaceControlGrid, resolution\);) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(console.log\(`\\nGenerated Mesh \(${mesh.length}x${mesh[0].length}\):`\);) Tj
T*
(console.log\(`Point at u=1, v=1: x=${mesh[3][3].x}, y=${mesh[3][3].y}, z=${mesh[3][3].z}`\);) Tj
T*
(// Output will match the bottom-right corner control point: x=10, y=10, z=0) Tj
T*
